    "content": "Bad idea.\n\nThe 道德仁义礼 passage is not an *illustration* of a general argument that could be swapped for another example. It is the argument itself -- a philosophical experiment that works by *reversing* a specific hierarchical chain the reader is following in real time. The experiential force depends on the reader first accepting the top-down order (道 generates 德 generates 仁 generates 义 generates 礼) and then watching it invert. A Western example (e.g., Platonic Forms generating particulars) would demonstrate the same *point* but would not produce the same *experience*, because the five-layer Chinese chain has a granularity and internal logic that makes the reversal vivid at each step.\n\nMore importantly: this is a Chinese author writing from within Chinese philosophical materials. Replacing the Chinese example with a Western one to ease translation would be a betrayal of the text's identity. The translation apparatus exists to serve the text, not the other way around. The reader who picks up 境集 has already accepted that they are reading a Chinese philosophical work. Trust them to follow the glosses."
